In order to make the project comprehensive, I wanted to write a script in communication with the user rather than proceeding with default values. Accordingly, the users have to enter:

    • Datasets csv files full path on their computer or
    • Datasets csv files name if it is in the same location as script or
    • Datasets csv files link if its a file on the internet
  • The number of the column to be used as the final grade label
  • The name of the preprocessing method (the list is given)
  • The name of the transformation method (the list is given)
  • The name of the training method (the list is given)

In addition, in order to keep the events in the script under the users control, users will need to answer the following questions:

  • After preprocessing is applied to the training data

    Do you want to see feature plots (y/n):

  • Before creating training models with different methods

    Would you like to see the Model Accuracies and Variable Importance plots of the training models? one-by-one (1) or in direct comparison (2)?

  • After creating at least 3 training models

    Do you want to continue for more models (y/n):

Apart from these, the program uses this function and waits for the user to press enter after each output that the user may want to examine.

wait_user <- function() {
  readline(prompt = "\n(Press enter to skip)\n")
}

2. Script

  • There is a function for each section.
  • There is a main function as the wrapper function that runs all functions.

First of all, I will examine each section with short explanations without outputs. Later, I will show how all the code works with the Online Shoppers Intertion data set by running it in a section. However, since the system cannot take inputs from user while creating the html file, I will modify the code in this way and use it.

Commands that affect the visual of the program and interaction with the user, such as writeLines ("") or wait_user(), will not be included in the code sections written to examine the functions.

Variables

First of all, since I will explain the functions first, I would like to explain the variables that are in the parameters of the functions but are calculated or found in the main function, that is, the function we will see last.

Variable Name Variable Value
n_col the number of columns of the original dataset
y_column_no the number of the column to be used as the final grade label
columns list, contains all columns names according to the location of the original dataset
answer response from the user represents decisions made
all_models list, contains all training models
all_models_names character group, contains all traning methods names

2.1.1. Import Dataset

import_df <- function() {
  ds_path = readline(prompt = "Enter the dataset's path for 'read.csv()' command:
                               (full path, name or link) ");
  df <- read.csv(ds_path)
  return(df)
}

This function imports the dataset by using the string taken from user.

2.1.2. Data Exploration

exploration <- function(df, n_col) {
  # The internal structure of dataset 
  print(str(df))
  
  writeLines("First 4 columns and their first 6 rows:\n")
  print(head(df[, 1:4]))
  
  n_col_3 <- n_col - 3
  
  writeLines("\nLast 4 columns and their first 6 rows:\n")
  print(head(df[, n_col_3 : n_col]))
}

This function presents the internal structure of the dataset that is taken as a parameter, and its the first and last 4 columns with their first 6 rows in order to explore the data.

2.1.3. Data Preparation

preparation <- function(df, y_column_no) {
  set.seed(100)
  
  # Step 1: Get row numbers for the train data
  trainRowNumbers <- createDataPartition(df[,y_column_no], p=0.8, list=FALSE)
  
  # Step 2: Create the training  dataset
  trainData <- df[trainRowNumbers,]
  
  # Step 3: Create the test dataset
  testData <- df[-trainRowNumbers,]
  
  # Store Y for later use
  y = as.factor(trainData[,y_column_no])
  
  skimmed <- skim(trainData)
  writeLines("\nFor The Training Data:")
  print(skimmed)
  
  return(list(trainData, testData, x, y))
}

This selects 80 percent of the dataset whick is taken as parameter, to use for training. It stores the remaining 20 percent to be used for testing, and the final grade label as y for later use. Finally, it presents a broad overview of the dataset.

2.1.4. Data Preprocessing

preprocessing <- function(trainData, y, columns, y_column_no) {
  
  # Missing Data Imputation
  
  methods <- '  "BoxCox", "YeoJohnson", "expoTrans", "center", "scale", "range",
  "knnImpute", "bagImpute", "medianImpute", "pca", "ica",
  "spatialSign", "corr", "zv", "nzv", "conditionalX"'
  writeLines(methods)
  preprocess_method = readline(prompt = "Enter the preprocessing method from above list: ");
  
  # With the selected method, a preprocessing model is created to find missing data
  preProcess_missingdata_model <- preProcess(trainData, method=paste(preprocess_method))
  
  writeLines("About Preproccessing Model")
  print(preProcess_missingdata_model)
  
  # Model is applied to our training dataset
  trainData <- predict(preProcess_missingdata_model, newdata = trainData)
  
  writeLines("After using this model to predict the missing values in trainData,")
  writeLines(paste("Is there any missing data?", anyNA(trainData)))
  
  
  # Converting Categorical Variables
  
  # Dummy variables are converting a categorical variable to 
  # as many binary variables as here are categories
  dummies_model <- dummyVars(as.formula( paste(columns[y_column_no], " ~ .") ), data = trainData)
  writeLines("Dummy variables that is converting a categorical variable to as many binary variables as\nhere are categories, are created.\n")
  
  # Model is applied to our training dataset
  trainData_mat <- predict(dummies_model, newdata = trainData)
  trainData <- data.frame(trainData_mat)
  
  # The internal structure of the train data
  print(str(trainData))
  
  
  # Transform The Data
  
  methods <- '  1. range: Normalize values so it ranges between 0 and 1
  2. center: Subtract Mean
  3. scale: Divide by standard deviation
  4. BoxCox: Remove skewness leading to normality. Values must be > 0
  5. YeoJohnson: Like BoxCox, but works for negative values.
  6. expoTrans: Exponential transformation, works for negative values.
  7. pca: Replace with principal components'
  writeLines(methods)
  
  transform_method = readline(prompt = "Enter the name of the transformation method from above list: ");
  
  # With the selected method, a preprocessing model is created to transform the data
  preProcess_transformation_model <- preProcess(trainData, method=paste(transform_method))
  
  # Model is applied to our training dataset
  trainData <- predict(preProcess_transformation_model, newdata = trainData)
  
  # The final grade label is added to training dataset
  trainData[[ columns[y_column_no] ]] <- y
  
  # The internal structure of the train data
  print(str(trainData))
  
  return(list(trainData, preProcess_missingdata_model, dummies_model, preProcess_transformation_model))
}

This function does 3 basic things:

  • Missing data imputation

    It creates a preprocessing model by taking the name of the method from user, to find missing data, shares it with users and applies this to the train data. After applying, it checks is there any missing data in train data.

  • Converting categorical variables

    It creates dummy variables that are converting a categorical variable to as many binary variables as here are categories, and applies this to the train data. After applying, it presents the internal structure of the train dataset.

    But there is a problem here: Some of the categorical columns are not perceived as categorical due to their form. Therefore, they are treated like a continuous column, without being categorized. The solution to this problem, on the other hand, does not always give correct results if the programs do it themselves. Solutions involving the user can be produced, but I could not deal with this issue as I was not able to run my time.

  • Transform the data

    It creates a transformation model by taking the name of the method from user, to transform the form of the data, and applies this to the train data. After applying, it adds y variable as the final grade label column to the train data. Then, it presents the internal structure of the train dataset.

2.1.5. Feature Plots

show_feature_plots <- function(trainData, columns, y_column_no) {
  # plot except the final grade label
  n_col_train <- ncol(trainData)
  n_col_train_1 <- n_col_train - 1
  
  writeLines("\nBox plot is loading...")
  show(featurePlot(x = trainData[, 1:n_col_train_1], 
              y = trainData[[ columns[y_column_no] ]], 
              plot = "box",
              strip=strip.custom(par.strip.text=list(cex=.7)),
              scales = list(x = list(relation="free"), 
                            y = list(relation="free"))))
  
  writeLines("Density plot is loading...")
  show(featurePlot(x = trainData[, 1:n_col_train_1], 
              y = trainData[[ columns[y_column_no] ]], 
              plot = "density",
              strip=strip.custom(par.strip.text=list(cex=.7)),
              scales = list(x = list(relation="free"), 
                            y = list(relation="free"))))
}

Its aim is very simple: to plot box and density plots of the train data.

2.1.6. Training

training <- function(trainData, answer, all_models_names, columns, y_column_no) {
  set.seed(100)
  
  methods <- '  "knn", "naive_bayes", "lda", "rpart", "adaboost",
  "bagFDAGCV", "parRF", "rf", "rfRules", "RRF", "gbm", 
  "xgbDART", "xgbLinear", "xgbTree", "bag", "C5.0"
  "C5.0Cost", "C5.0Rules", "C5.0Tree", "fda", "bagEarth", 
  "bagEarthGCV", "earth", "gcvEarth", "bagFDA", "ranger",
  "svmLinear2", "svmLinearWeights", "ordinalRF", "treebag"'
  writeLines(methods)
  
  training_method = readline(prompt = "  Enter the training method from above list: 
  (There are more than these but this script's libraries contains them)");
  
  writeLines("\nThe model is being trained...")
  training_model = train(as.formula( paste(columns[y_column_no], " ~ .") ), data=trainData, method=paste(training_method))
  
  # For being able to name the models in the list that contains all models
  all_models_names <- c(all_models_names, paste(training_method))
  
  if (answer == 1){
    writeLines("\nModel Accuracies plot loading...")
    try(show(plot(training_model, main="Model Accuracies")))
    
    writeLines("Variable Importance plot loading...")
    varimp <- varImp(training_model)
    show(plot(varimp, main="Variable Importance"))
  }
  
  return(list(training_model, all_models_names))
}

It creates a training model by taking the methods name from the user. Also, it adds methods name to the all_models_names list to use later.

If the user answered yes to the question Would you like to see the Model Accuracies and Variable Importance plots of the training models, it prints the Model Accuracies and Variable Importance plots.

2.1.7. Prediction

prediction <- function(testData, preProcess_missingdata_model, dummies_model, preProcess_transformation_model, answer) {
  # Step 1: Impute missing values 
  testData2 <- predict(preProcess_missingdata_model, testData)
  
  # Step 2: Create one-hot encodings (dummy variables)
  testData2 <- predict(dummies_model, testData2)
  
  # Step 3: Transform the features with selected method
  testData2 <- predict(preProcess_transformation_model, testData2)
  
  # The internal structure of the test data
  writeLines("Test data after preprocessing models are applied:")
  print(str(data.frame(testData2)))
  
  return(testData2)
}

It applies the models we created in the Preprocessing step to the test data set and presents the internal structure of it.

2.1.8. Performance Evaluation

performance_evaluation <- function(testData, testData2, training_model, columns, y_column_no) {
  # Test data is predicted by using training model
  fitted <- predict(training_model, testData2)
  
  # Calculates a cross-tabulation of observed and predicted classes with associated statistics
  show(caret::confusionMatrix(reference = as.factor(testData[[ columns[y_column_no] ]]), data = fitted, mode='everything'))
}

It makes predictions on test data using the training model which is taken as a parameter. Then, it calculates a cross-tabulation of observed and predicted classes with associated statistics.

2.1.9. Comparison

comparison <- function(all_models) {
  # Model performances are compared
  models_compare <- resamples(all_models)
  
  # Summary of the models performances
  summary(models_compare)
  
  # Box plots to compare models
  scales <- list(x=list(relation="free"), y=list(relation="free"))
  writeLines("\nModel Compare plot is loading...")
  show(bwplot(models_compare, scales=scales))
}

It compares the performances of all training models created, presents the summary of the comparison and visualizes it with the box plot.

2.2. Main

main <- function() {
  # Import the Dataset
  df <- import_df()
  
  n_col <- ncol(df) # to be used in many functions
  exploration(df, n_col)   # Data Exploration
  
  y_column_no = readline(prompt = "  Enter the number of the column to be used as the final grade label: 
  For example 18 for 'online_shoppers_intention.csv'");
  y_column_no = as.integer(y_column_no);
  
  # Data Preparation
  c(trainData, testData, y) %<-% preparation(df, y_column_no)
  
  # all names according to the location of the original data set
  # This is used when specific column names are required
  columns <- names(df)
  
  # Data Preprocessing
  c(trainData, preProcess_missingdata_model, dummies_model, preProcess_transformation_model) %<-% preprocessing(trainData, y, columns, y_column_no)
  
  answer = readline(prompt = "Do you want to see feature plots (y/n):")
  answer <- "no"
  if (toupper(answer) == "Y" || toupper(answer) == "YES") {
    show_feature_plots(trainData, columns, y_column_no)
  }
  
  answer = readline("  Would you like to see the Model Accuracies and Variable Importance plots
  of the training models? one-by-one (1) or in direct comparison (2)? ")
  answer <- as.integer(answer)
  
  all_models <- list()      # to keep all training models
  all_models_names <- c()   # to keep all training models names
  
  cont <- "yes"
  # To create the desired number of training models
  while (toupper(cont) == "Y" || toupper(cont) == "YES") {
    # Training
    c(training_model, all_models_names) %<-% training(trainData, answer, all_models_names, columns, y_column_no)
    
    # add new training model to list
    all_models <- c(all_models, list(training_model))
    
    # Comparison can be made after at least 3 models
    if (length(all_models) > 2) {
      cont = readline(prompt = "Do you want to continue for more models (y/n):")
    }
    
  }
  
  # Names in the list are replaced with the names of models
  names(all_models) <- all_models_names
  
  # Comparison of Models
  comparison(all_models)
  
  # Application of preprocessing steps to the test data
  testData2 <- prediction(testData, preProcess_missingdata_model, dummies_model, preProcess_transformation_model)
  
  # Predictions
  writeLines(toupper("Predicting Test Data with All Models"))
  for (i in 1:length(all_models)) {
    writeLines(paste(i, ". For", toupper(all_models_names[[i]]), "model:"))
    performance_evaluation(testData, testData2, all_models[[i]], columns, y_column_no)
  }
}

Our main function that we will call wrapper function.

  1. Imports the dataset with import_df()

  2. Creates n_col variable

  3. Explores the dataset with exploration()

  4. Takes y_column_no variable from the user

  5. Do preparations with preparation()

  6. Creates columns variable

  7. Make preprocessing with preprocessing()

  8. Takes answer variable from the user

  9. Depend on the answer variable, shows plots with show_feature_plots()

  10. Takes a new answer variable from the user

  11. Creates an empty list named all_models

  12. Creates an empty characther group named all_models_names

  13. Creates cont variable with yes value

  14. Depend on the cont variable;

  • Creates a training model

  • Adds model to the all_models list

  • Asks the user if they want to change the value of the cont variable

  1. Changes all_models names with all_models_names

  2. Compares all models with comparison()

  3. Applies all preproccessing models to the test data with prediction()

  4. Predictes the test data with all training models with performance_evaluation()

3. Demostrate

I rearranged the code so that it does not require input from the user. Accordingly;

  • Uses the file online_shoppers_intention.csv, which is supposed to be in the same location as the script, as the data set.

  • Uses knnImpute method for missing values and range method for transformation in preprocessing step.

  • Uses the value 18 for the variable y_column_no and c (" knn , naive_bayes , lda , earth , fda ) forall_models_names"

  • Creates training models with all_models_names values as methods

  • Prints Model Accuracies and Variable Importance plots for each model, and feature plots for the training set.
